Metabolites are constantly on a journey traveling through biochemical pathways over time. How they travel and where they end up gives biochemists a clue on the cellular physiology, morphology, behavior and disease states especially cardiovascular diseases, neurodegenerative diseases and cancer. This lesson introduces the key concept of metabolic flux and how these biochemical journeys look. The lesson is intended for the undergraduate level of biochemistry and metabolism students, but could be useful to other trainees as well. See the lesson chapters below to learn more.
Background Knowledge
This lesson is complementary to introductory classes in metabolism that cover homeostasis and principles of kinetics to describe flux through biochemical pathways. The students should be learning about catabolism of nutrient molecules such as carbohydrates, lipids and proteins, and their anabolism into storage and structural molecules to appreciate the lesson. They should also be familiar with redox reactions and terms oxidation and reduction.&nbsp;

Discover virtual lab simulations designed to support the objectives set out in the AP Biology Lab Manual. AP Biology is an advanced, college-level course taught at the high school level that prepares students for introductory biology in college.&nbsp;
These inquiry-based investigations support students to practice essential laboratory skills and apply knowledge to solve real-world biological problems. Emphasis is placed on critical thinking, data analysis, and application-based assessments that mirror the rigor of college-level coursework.&nbsp;
