The relationship between race and science has a long history that&rsquo;s important for us to explore. Historically, members of the scientific and medical communities used false ideas about race to justify colonialism and slavery. Other members took advantage of racially marginalized groups to further medical research. This history has contributed to inequalities in health care that persist today.
In this pathway, we explore these aspects of our history. We look at the impact of events such as slavery, the US Civil War, and infectious disease epidemics on the health of racially marginalized groups. We also examine the mistreatment of racially marginalized groups in medical research. By doing so, we can avoid further instances of racial discrimination in modern science and medicine, and address the health inequalities that this history has contributed to.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the Racism as a Public Health Crisis cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative. Please note: This pathway contains sensitive content related to racial violence and discrimination.

How does systemic racism affect the experiences of racially diverse students in STEM? And why is it important for educators to recognize and address its impact in their classrooms?&nbsp;
In this pathway, we&rsquo;ll explore these questions by examining how racism operates as a system in US society and has become embedded in educational institutions. We&rsquo;ll also consider how different forms of racism create barriers to learning, which impact the everyday experiences&mdash;and often the career paths&mdash;of Black, Hispanic, and Indigenous students in STEM.&nbsp;
Finally, we&rsquo;ll introduce strategies that educators and institutions can use to raise awareness of these issues and address them. By confronting the effects of systemic racism in schools, educators and institutions can take an important step toward creating more equitable and inclusive learning environments for all students.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the Advancing Equity in STEM through Inclusive Teaching cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative.

When we look at the differences in people&rsquo;s appearances around the globe&mdash;such as variations in skin tone, body proportions, and hair texture&mdash;it&rsquo;s clear that the human species is incredibly diverse. Historically, societies have classified people into races based on these differences. However, when we look at our biology more closely, the human species is not as different as it may appear.
In this pathway, we explore the characteristics of human genetic diversity, which relates to the patterns of variation in our genes. By grounding our understanding in evolutionary science, we&rsquo;ll recognize how these genetic patterns challenge historical understandings of race. They reveal that the concept of race in humans has been created by society, and has no biological basis.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the&nbsp;Racism as a Public Health Crisis&nbsp;cluster.&nbsp;See our&nbsp;equity pledge&nbsp;as part of this initiative.&nbsp;Please note: This pathway contains sensitive content related to racial violence and discrimination.

Does where we are born, live, learn, or play have an impact on our health? Social and environmental determinants of health are factors in our environments, both past and present, that influence our health outcomes and quality of life. Unfortunately, not everyone has the same access to positive social and environmental determinants of health. In the US, systemic racism continues to prevent many Black, Hispanic, and Indigenous communities from accessing educational opportunities, having a stable income, or living in neighborhoods that are free from pollutants.&nbsp;
In this pathway, we&rsquo;ll explore the influence of systemic racism on health outcomes, particularly by understanding the history of residential segregation in the US. Through various case studies, we&rsquo;ll explore how this history and other forms of discrimination continue to impact the health of racially marginalized groups today.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the Racism as a Public Health Crisis cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative. Please note: This pathway contains sensitive content related to racial violence and discrimination.

What unique barriers do Black, Hispanic, and Indigenous students encounter in STEM classrooms?&nbsp;
This pathway explores three key barriers to learning and thriving in STEM&mdash;stereotype threat, bias, and microaggressions. It examines how systemic racism in society and STEM institutions contributes to these barriers and how they impact the experiences, motivation, and academic performance of racially diverse students.&nbsp;
Finally, it introduces strategies for STEM educators to recognize and address stereotype threat, bias, and microaggressions in their classrooms. By doing so, educators can create safer and more equitable learning environments that promote the success of all students in STEM.
This pathway forms part of the Advancing Equity in STEM through Inclusive Teaching cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative.

How do educators&rsquo; beliefs about intelligence shape their students&rsquo; performance? While systemic racism and historical inequalities influence academic disparities, educators&rsquo; mindsets are another key factor&mdash;and one that they are able to change.&nbsp;
This pathway examines the mindsets that STEM educators bring to their classrooms. It focuses on the benefits of a growth mindset&mdash;the belief that all students can develop their abilities through effort and support&mdash;and metacognition&mdash;the awareness of one&rsquo;s own thought processes. It also explores practical ways to use growth mindset and metacognitive learning strategies in STEM lessons. By believing in every student&rsquo;s potential for growth, educators can help to create more equitable opportunities for success in STEM.
This pathway forms part of the Advancing Equity in STEM through Inclusive Teaching cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative.

How can STEM educators advance racial equity and promote the success of all students in their classes?
An inclusive classroom is a learning environment in which all students are equitably supported and included, regardless of their identities, learning preferences, abilities, or backgrounds. This pathway describes the characteristics of an inclusive classroom and outlines related activities that educators can integrate into their STEM lessons. It also introduces inclusive classroom management and arrangement strategies to make all aspects of the learning environment welcoming and engaging, particularly for students from racially diverse backgrounds.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the Advancing Equity in STEM through Inclusive Teaching cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative.

In the US, white students are consistently more likely to complete STEM degrees than Black, Hispanic, and Indigenous students. Why does this disparity exist, and how can educators more equitably support all students&rsquo; success in STEM?&nbsp;
A key factor that influences student success is persistence&mdash;the ability to persevere through challenges in their STEM academic journey. This pathway examines the concept of persistence and outlines the systemic barriers that often undermine the persistence of racially diverse students in STEM. It also explores the crucial role that educators play in cultivating students&rsquo; self-efficacy and STEM identity&mdash;two essential traits that support persistence. By building students&rsquo; confidence and ability to see themselves as STEM contributors, educators can support all students in developing the persistence they need to achieve their academic goals.
This pathway forms part of the Advancing Equity in STEM through Inclusive Teaching cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative.

The major ecological and social crisis that Planet Earth, its territories, living environments and inhabitants are going through, makes it necessary to deal with systemic, multidisciplinary and interdisciplinary issues related to the environment. The increased sensitivity to the effects of human activities on the major balances of the biosphere, primarily climate change, the extinction of biodiversity, pollution, the considerable pressure on natural resources and settlement dynamics, raise important political and social debates. The major cycles such as water, carbon, nitrogen, the major telluric or climatic phenomena, energy resources, are all processes that must be rethought today in their interactions with human activities.&nbsp;
The &ldquo;Ecological challenges from a multidisciplinary perspective&rdquo; seminar series of the EPOG+ Erasmus Mundus programme is jointly organised by the University of Paris&rsquo; Earth Politics Centre, the Sorbonne University&rsquo;s Institute for Environmental Transition and the Graduate school &ldquo;Sustainability and transitions&rdquo;. All the sessions are given by world-specialist in the addressed field.
For the programme and online (live) attendance: https://ec.epog.eu

How can we address the preventable health disparities that exist between different communities in the US&mdash;particularly those that affect racially marginalized groups? One approach is by working toward health equity.&nbsp;
Health equity involves the provision of fair and just opportunities for all people to be as healthy as possible, no matter who they are, where they live, or how much money they make. In this pathway, we&rsquo;ll explore the importance of health equity and learn about different kinds of interventions that can help us achieve it. We&rsquo;ll look at the roles that all people&mdash;such as policymakers, community members, and health-care professionals&mdash;can play in striving toward health equity. We&rsquo;ll also investigate case studies of successful health equity interventions in the US.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the Racism as a Public Health Crisis cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative. Please note: This pathway contains sensitive content related to racial violence and discrimination.&nbsp;

Culturally relevant pedagogy draws on all students&rsquo; cultural backgrounds as resources for learning. In STEM, this approach helps educators to address the cultural inequities that impact certain students&rsquo; opportunities for success.&nbsp;
This pathway introduces culturally relevant pedagogy and its three components&mdash;student achievement, cultural competence, and critical consciousness&mdash;and outlines their benefits in STEM classrooms. Educators will discover practical strategies to integrate this approach into their teaching practices, fostering more inclusive, engaging, and effective learning experiences for all students.&nbsp;
This pathway forms part of the&nbsp;Advancing Equity in STEM through Inclusive Teaching cluster. See our equity pledge as part of this initiative.

